TI  - Dual adaptive soft thresholding multimodal networks with contrastive augmentation for intrapartum fetal monitoring
PY  - 2026
T2  - Engineering Applications of Artificial Intelligence
VL  - 170
C7  - 114179
DO  - 10.1016/j.engappai.2026.114179
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105030228069&doi=10.1016%2Fj.engappai.2026.114179&partnerID=40&md5=ca81fb72dbc21b2a0ae44a2ecfdfa380
AB  - During labor, obstetricians assess fetal health status through integrated analysis of cardiotocography (CTG) recording fetal heart rate (FHR) and uterine contraction (UC) signals, and maternal clinical data. While recent deep learning (DL)-based CTG classifying methods demonstrate enhanced objectivity compared to manual interpretation, two critical limitations persist. Interpretation of UC signals aids in labor assessment, yet few studies have developed dedicated denoising techniques for intrapartum UC signals. Additionally, existing research either concentrates on FHR analysis or fails to comprehensively fuse FHR, UC signals, and maternal clinical data. To address these limitations, we propose the Dual Adaptive Soft Thresholding Multimodal Networks (DAST-MMNet), which dynamically suppresses extrinsic noise in intrapartum UC signals and cross-modal interference during feature fusion. Moreover, a contrastive augmentation strategy is integrated with focal loss to address the class imbalance problem, combined with a re-mask mechanism that prioritizes discriminative features during decision-making. Experimental results demonstrate that DAST-MMNet achieved superior sensitivity while maintaining robust overall performance compared to state-of-the-art DL models. Under 20% noise interference, the DAST mechanism demonstrated 42.55%, 94.56%, and 21.97% improvements in F1-score, Matthews Correlation Coefficient (MCC), and Area Under the Curve (AUC) respectively over baselines. Finally, Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping plus (Grad-CAM++) was employed to interpret the model’s decision-making process systematically. In summary, this study advances noise-resistant multimodal intelligent intrapartum fetal monitoring. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.
